Feature Engeering¶

Transfer BMI to categorical

https://www.nhs.uk/common-health-questions/lifestyle/what-is-the-body-mass-index-bmi/

below 18.5 you're in the underweight range between 18.5 and 24.9 you're in the healthy weight range between 25 and 29.9 you're in the overweight range between 30 and 39.9 you're in the obese range

In [ ]:
df_new['BMI'] = df_new['BMI'].astype(float)
In [ ]:
df_new['BMI'] = pd.cut(x=df_new['BMI'],
                     bins=[0,18.5,25,30,100],
                     labels=['underweight', 'healthy weight', 'overweight',"obese"])

Hillclimbsearch¶

Hillclimbsearch is a heuristic search approach that can be used with larger number of nodes. It implements a greedy local search that starts from the DAG start (default: disconnected DAG) and proceeds by iteratively performing single-edge manipulations that maximally increase the score. The search terminates once a local maximum is found.

In [ ]:
# Hillclimbsearch
model = bn.structure_learning.fit(df_train, methodtype='hc', scoretype='bic')

G = bn.plot(model)

Manually created DAG¶

Create a custom Directed Acyclic Graph.

In [ ]:
edges = [('Sex', 'Smoker'),
         ('Sex', 'Diabetes_012'),
         ('Sex', 'HeartDiseaseorAttack'),
         ('Sex', 'BMI'),
         ('Veggies', 'HighBP'),
         ('Veggies', 'HeartDiseaseorAttack'),
         ('Veggies', 'BMI'),
         ('Stroke', 'HighChol'),
         ('Stroke', 'Age'),
         ('Stroke', 'HighBP'),
         ('Stroke', 'HeartDiseaseorAttack'),
         ('Stroke', 'BMI'),
         ('Stroke', 'Diabetes_012'),
         ('HighChol', 'Diabetes_012'),
         ('HighChol', 'HighBP'),
         ('HighChol', 'Age'),
         ('Age', 'BMI'),
         ('HighBP', 'HeartDiseaseorAttack'),
         ('HighBP', 'Age'),
         ('HighBP', 'Diabetes_012'),
         ('HighBP', 'BMI'),
         ('Smoker', 'BMI'),
         ('Smoker', 'Age'),
         ('Diabetes_012', 'BMI'),
         ('Diabetes_012', 'Age'),
         ('Diabetes_012', 'HeartDiseaseorAttack'),
         ('Diabetes_012', 'Smoker'),
         ('Fruits', 'BMI'), 
         ('HeartDiseaseorAttack', 'Age'),
         ('HeartDiseaseorAttack', 'BMI'),
         ('HvyAlcoholConsump', 'Age'),
         ('HvyAlcoholConsump', 'BMI'),
         ('HvyAlcoholConsump', 'Smoker')]
In [ ]:
# Create the DAG from the edges. Plot it.
DAG = bn.make_DAG(edges)

bn.plot(DAG)
#bn.plot(DAG, interactive=True)

Compute Conditional Probability Distributions (CPDs).¶

Now using the data set in the dataframe (df) estimate conditional distributions (CPDs). Do it using the method parameter_learning.fit().

Check first if there are any conditional distributions in the model.

In [ ]:
bn.print_CPD(DAG)

[bnlearn] >No CPDs to print. Hint: Add CPDs as following: <bn.make_DAG(DAG, CPD=[cpd_A, cpd_B, etc])> and use bnlearn.plot(DAG) to make a plot.
In [ ]:
DAG = bn.parameter_learning.fit(DAG, df_train, methodtype='bayes')

# Get score
def get_acc(model, df, col):
    # Get accuracy score by the model for the validation dataset df with target col
    pred = bn.predict(model, df, variables=[col])
    print(pred)
    acc = accuracy_score(df[col], pred[col])
    print('Accuracy -', acc)
    return acc
